tario|Markham]] east of [[Ontario Highway 48]] / Main Street Markham/ [[York Regional Road 68]] was incorporated into the new [[Markham\u2014Stouffville]] riding.<ref>[http://www.redecoupage-federal-redistribution.ca/content.asp?section=on&dir=now/proposals/35052&document=index&lang=e Markham\u2014Stouffville \u2013 Proposed Boundaries]</ref> The part in the town of [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]] is part of the new [[Aurora\u2014Oak Ridges\u2014Richmond Hill]] riding.<ref>[http://www.redecoupage-federal-redistribution.ca/content.asp?section=on&dir=now/proposals/35004&document=index&lang=e Aurora\u2014Richmond Hill \u2013 Proposed Boundaries]</ref> Finally, the part in the city of [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]] west of the above-mentioned roads is part of the new [[Markham\u2014Unionville]] riding,<ref>[http://www.redecoupage-federal-redistribution.ca/content.asp?section=on&dir=now/proposals/35053&document=index&lang=e Markham\u2014Unionville \u2013 Proposed Boundaries]</ref> which is different from the previous riding of the same name.\n\n==References==\n*{{SCref|unit=fed|name=2011fed|accessdate=2011-03-03|35059}}\n*[http://webinfo.parl.gc.ca/MembersOfParliament/ProfileConstituency.aspx?Key=449&Language=E Oak Ridges\u2014Markham] constituency profile at the [[Parliament of Canada]]\n* [http://enr.elections.ca/ElectoralDistricts_e.aspx?type=3&criteria=Oak_Ridges--Markham 2011 results from Elections Canada]\n*[https://archive.is/20130115121152/http://www.elections.ca/scripts/pss/Profile.aspx?L=E&ED=35059&EV=99 Electoral district profile Oak Ridges--Markham (Ontario)]\n*[http://www.elections.ca Campaign expense data from Elections Canada]\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.parl.gc.ca/Parliamentarians/en/constituencies/Oak-Ridges-Markham%28449%29 Oak Ridges\u2014Markham] at Parliament of Canada\n\n{{Ridings in Southern Durham and York}}\n{{Ridings in Ontario}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oak Ridges-Markham}}\n[[Category:Defunct Ontario federal electoral districts]]\n[[Category:Politics of King, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politics of Markham, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politics of Richmond Hill, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Whitchurch\u2013Stouffville]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the provincial electoral district|Oak Ridges\u2014Markham (provincial electoral district)}}\n{{One source|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox Canada electoral district\n| province            = Ontario\n| image               = Oak Ridges-Markham.png\n| caption             = Oak Ridges\u2014Markham is in south-central Ontario, just north of Toronto\n| coordinates         = {{coord|43|55|45|N|79|31|37|W|region:CA-ON_type:landmark_dim:50km|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_caption = Location of the federal district constituency office in [[King City, Ontario|King City]]\n| coordinates_date    = 2010-08-26\n| fed-status          = defunct\n| fed-district-number = 35059\n| fed-created         = 2003\n| fed-abolished       = 2013\n| fed-election-first  = 2004\n| fed-election-last   = 2011\n| fed-rep             = \n| fed-rep-party       = \n| fed-rep-party-link  = \n| demo-pop-ref        = <ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[#2011fed|Statistics Canada]]: 2012</ref>\n| demo-area-ref       = <ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n| demo-electors-ref   = \n| demo-census-date    = [[Canada 2011 Census|2011]]\n| demo-pop            = 228997\n| demo-electors       = 151584\n| demo-electors-date  = 2011\n| demo-area           = 679.90\n| demo-cd             = [[York Regional Municipality, Ontario|York]]\n| demo-csd            = [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]], [[Whitchurch\u2013Stouffville]], [[King, Ontario|King]]\n}}\n\n[[Image:Oak Ridges-Markham (riding map).png|thumb|right|250px|Map of Oak Ridges-Markham]]\n\n'''Oak Ridges\u2014Markham''' was a federal [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] in [[Ontario]], Canada, that was represented in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] from 2004 to 2015. Its population in 2006 was 169,645.,<ref name=\"2006pop\">{{Cite web\n  | url = http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-595/P2C.cfm?TPL=RETR&LANG=E&GC=35059\n  | title = Federal Electoral District Profile of Oak Ridges&nbsp;\u2014 Markham, Ontario (2003 Representation Order), 2006 Census\n  | publisher = [[Statistics Canada]]\n  | accessdate =2010-04-04\n}}</ref> with 136,755 electors, the highest of any [[List of Canadian federal electoral districts|riding in Canada]]. By 2011, the riding's population had risen to 228,997, the largest population of all ridings in Canada.<ref>Census Canada, [http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/popdwell/Table.cfm?T=501&SR=1&S=5&O=D&RPP=9999&PR=0&CMA=0 Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and federal electoral districts], 2006; National Post, [http://news.nationalpost.com/2012/02/08/canada-census-2011-tories-could-reap-the-benefits-as-census-suggests-new-ridings/ Canada Census 2011: Harper could reap the benefits as census suggests new ridings], February 8, 2012.</ref>\n\nThe district covered part of the suburbs north of [[Toronto]]. It included the town of [[Whitchurch\u2013Stouffville]], most of the township of [[King, Ontario|King]] (excepting extreme northeast) the northern portions of the town of [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]] (including all of [[Oak Ridges, Ontario|Oak Ridges]]), and the northern and eastern portions of the city of [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]].\n\nThe electoral district was created in 2004 52.5% from [[Oak Ridges (electoral district)|Oak Ridges]], 30% from [[Markham (electoral district)|Markham]], 13% from [[Vaughan\u2014King\u2014Aurora]], and 4.5% from [[York North]] riding.\n\nFollowing the [[Canadian federal electoral redistribution, 2012|2012 federal electoral boundaries redistribution]], the district was split between [[King\u2014Vaughan]], [[Aurora\u2014Oak Ridges\u2014Richmond Hill]], [[Markham\u2014Unionville]], and [[Markham\u2014Stouffville]].\n\n==Demographics==\nCommunities in Oak Ridges\u2014Markham are the destination for many [[Immigration to Canada|immigrants to Canada]], composing about 41.6% of the population, or about 70,000 of its residents.<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> For 72,440 residents, neither English nor French, the [[Official bilingualism in Canada|official languages of Canada]], is their mother tongue,<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> though most have knowledge of English (148,975), French (160), or both (12,885).<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> Most immigrants [[Canadian nationality law#Naturalization as a Canadian citizen|become citizens]], as 11,155 immigrants were not Canadian citizens as of the [[Canada 2006 Census]].<ref name=\"2006pop\" />\n\nThe primarily urban district has a low proportion of [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal residents]] compared to other parts of Canada, with just 625 people identifying themselves of such descent.<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> It is also home to 70,070 residents who identify themselves as [[Visible minority|visible minorities]], more than half of which are [[Chinese Canadian]]s<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> and about 20% are [[Black Canadians]].<ref name=\"2006pop\" />\n\nAt the 2006 census, the [[participation rate]] of residents in the work force was 71.3%, and the electoral district [[unemployment rate]] was 5%,<ref name=\"2006pop\" /> below the national average of 6.3%.<ref name=\"canadaUR\">{{cite web\n  | url = http://www4.hrsdc.gc.ca/.3ndic.1t.4r@-eng.jsp?iid=16\n  | title =  Work&nbsp;\u2014 Unemployment Rate\n  | publisher = [[Human Resources and Skills Development Canada]]\n  | accessdate =2010-04-04\n}}</ref>\n\nThe district is the second-largest [[List of Canadian federal electoral districts|electoral district]] in Canada by population, next to [[Brampton West]] which had 170,422 residents at the 2006 census.<ref name=\"EDsize\">{{Cite web\n  | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-550/Index.cfm?TPL=P1C&Page=RETR&LANG=Eng&T=501&SR=1&S=3&O=D&RPP=9999&PR=0&CMA=0\n  | title = Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and federal electoral districts (2003 Representation Order), 2006 and 2001 censuses - 100% data (sorted by 2006 population)\n  | work = Federal electoral districts (FEDs)&nbsp;\u2013 2003 Representation Order\n  | publisher = Statistics Canada\n  | accessdate =2010-04-04\n}}</ref> It was the 64th largest in 2001, with a population of 111,276,<ref name=\"EDsize2\">{{Cite web\n  | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-550/Index.cfm?TPL=P1C&Page=RETR&LANG=Eng&T=501&SR=1&S=4&O=D&RPP=9999&PR=0&CMA=0\n  | title = Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and federal electoral districts (2003 Representation Order), 2006 and 2001 censuses - 100% data (sorted by 2001 population)\n  | work = Federal electoral districts (FEDs)&nbsp;\u2013 2003 Representation Order\n  | publisher = Statistics Canada\n  | accessdate =2010-04-04\n}}</ref> but had the greatest population growth from 2001 to 2006, about 52.5%.<ref name=\"EDsize3\">{{Cite web\n  | url = http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-550/Index.cfm?TPL=P1C&Page=RETR&LANG=Eng&T=501&SR=1&S=5&O=D&RPP=9999&PR=0&CMA=0\n  | title = Population and dwelling counts, for Canada and federal electoral districts (2003 Representation Order), 2006 and 2001 censuses - 100% data (sorted by population growth)\n  | work = Federal electoral districts (FEDs)&nbsp;\u2013 2003 Representation Order\n  | publisher = Statistics Canada\n  | accessdate =2010-04-04\n}}</ref>\n\n==Boundaries==\nAccording to Elections Canada, Oak Ridges\u2014Markham consisted of that part of the Regional Municipality of York composed of:\n\n(a) the Town of [[Whitchurch\u2013Stouffville]];\n\n(b) the part of the Township of [[King, Ontario|King]] south of Highway No. 9;\n\n(c) the part of the Town of [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]] lying north and east of a line drawn from the western town limit east along Gamble Road, south along Yonge Street and east along Elgin Mills Road East to the eastern town limit; and\n\n(d) the part of the City of [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]] lying north and east of a line drawn from the western town limit east along 16th Avenue, south along McCowan Road, east along Highway No. 7, and south along 9th Line to the southern town limit.\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n\nThis riding has elected the following member of the [[House of Commons of Canada]]:\n\n{{CanMP}}\n{{CanMP nodata|Oak Ridges\u2014Markham<br>''Riding created from'' [[Oak Ridges (electoral district)|Oak Ridges]], [[Markham (electoral district)|Markham]],<br>[[Vaughan\u2014King\u2014Aurora]] ''and'' [[York North]]}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2004\n| ToYr = 2006\n| Assembly# = 38\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = Lui Temelkovski\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2006\n| ToYr = 2008\n| Assembly# = 39\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2008\n| ToYr = 2011\n| Assembly# = 40\n| CanParty = Conservative\n| RepName = Paul Calandra\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 2011\n| ToYr = 2015\n| Assembly# = 41\n}}\n{{CanMP nodata|''Riding dissolved into'' [[Markham\u2014Stouffville]], [[King\u2014Vaughan]],<br> [[Markham\u2014Unionville]] ''and'' [[Aurora\u2014Oak Ridges\u2014Richmond Hill]]}}\n{{CanMP end}}\n\n==Election results==\n{{Image frame\n| content = {{Graph:Chart\n | width=400\n | height=300\n | type=line\n | xAxisTitle=Year\n | yAxisTitle=Vote share\n | xAxisMin=2004\n | xAxisMax=2011\n | yAxisMin=0\n | yAxisMax=0.5\n | yAxisFormat=%\n | legend=Legend\n | y1Title=Liberal\n | y2Title=Conservative\n | y3Title=NDP\n | y4Title=Green\n | y5Title=PC\n | y6Title=Reform/Alliance\n | linewidth=2\n | x=2004,2006,2008,2011\n | y1=0.5173,0.4705,0.4152,0.2826\n | y2=0.3351,0.3847,0.4224,0.5112\n | y3=0.0878,0.0988,0.0939,0.1684\n | y4=0.0389,0.0459,0.0683,0.026\n | colors=#DC241f,#1c1cff,#FAA61A,#6AB023\n | showSymbols=true }} \n| caption=Graph of general election results in Oak Ridges\u2014Markham (minor parties tha